{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775878133955,"sessionID":"ses_2856a97e0ffey48D6qOMQnb0po","part":{"id":"prt_d7a95d890001jp5aJthxqAebqf","messageID":"msg_d7a95bdbb001oiWBBemIMtsJ5c","sessionID":"ses_2856a97e0ffey48D6qOMQnb0po","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-73ce2e03548c42e7acca588b73a21b39","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-028/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-028/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-028: SDK AgentRuntimeClient\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: Implement the `AgentRuntimeClient` in the AgentCube Python SDK, providing a streamlined interface for invoking agent runtime workloads through the Router service. The client abstracts underlying HTTP communication, offering a simple, type-safe API for managing agent runtime sessions and invoking agent workloads with minimal boilerplate.\n6: \n7: ## Purpose\n8: \n9: Provide a Python SDK client for the AgentRuntime service with the following goals:\n10: \n11: - Simple, intuitive API for invoking agent runtime workloads\n12: - Automatic session ID bootstrap and management\n13: - Context manager support for automatic resource cleanup\n14: - Integrated Data Plane communication via Router\n15: - Proper error handling and timeout configuration\n16: - Detailed logging and debugging support\n17: \n18: ## Module\n19: \n20: `sdk-python`\n21: \n22: ## Language\n23: \n24: Python 3.10+\n25: \n26: ## Size\n27: \n28: M\n29: \n30: ## Scope\n31: \n32: ### In Scope\n33: \n34: 1. **AgentRuntimeClient Core Functionality**\n35:    - Session ID bootstrap from Router\n36:    - Agent workload invocation\n37:    - Context manager support (`__enter__` / `__exit__`)\n38:    - Resource cleanup\n39: \n40: 2. **Data Plane Integration**\n41:    - HTTP communication via Router\n42:    - Session header management (`x-agentcube-session-id`)\n43:    - Timeout configuration\n44:    - Connection pooling\n45: \n46: 3. **Configuration Management**\n47:    - Environment variable resolution (`ROUTER_URL`)\n48:    - Configurable timeouts (read, connect)\n49:    - Session ID reuse support\n50: \n51: 4. **Error Handling**\n52:    - Session validation\n53:    - HTTP error propagation\n54:    - Clear error messages\n55: \n56: ### Out of Scope\n57: \n58: - Agent lifecycle management (create, delete, list)\n59: - Session persistence and recovery\n60: - Streaming responses\n61: - Webhook support\n62: - Metrics and observability\n63: - Async API (can be added in future AR)\n64: - Custom retry logic\n65: \n66: ## Impact Analysis\n67: \n68: ### Components Impacted\n69: \n70: 1. **Python SDK Package Structure**\n71:    - New file: `agentcube/agent_runtime.py`\n72:    - New file: `agentcube/clients/agent_runtime_data_plane.py`\n73:    - Update `agentcube/__init__.py` exports\n74: \n75: 2. **Router Service (Data Plane)**\n76:    - GET `{router}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/` - Bootstrap session ID\n77:    - POST `{router}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/` - Invoke agent\n78: \n79: 3. **Developer Experience**\n80:    - Provide Python SDK documentation\n81:    - Example code for agent invocation\n82:    - pip package distribution\n83: \n84: 4. **Testing and CI/CD**\n85:    - Unit tests for client classes\n86:    - Integration tests with Router\n87:    - E2E testing\n88: \n89: ### Dependencies\n90: \n91: - `requests ^2.31.0` - HTTP client\n92: \n93: ### Breaking Changes\n94: \n95: None. This is a new SDK feature.\n96: \n97: ### Security Considerations\n98: \n99: 1. **Authentication**\n100:    - Router handles JWT validation\n101:    - Session ID transmitted via headers\n102:    - No auth token directly set by SDK\n103: \n104: 2. **Data Transmission**\n105:    - HTTPS recommended (production)\n106:    - Session ID via `x-agentcube-session-id` header\n107:    - Payloads as JSON\n108: \n109: 3. **Input Validation**\n110:    - Session ID validation before invoke\n111:    - Type checking via Python type hints\n112: \n113: ## Design Decisions\n114: \n115: ### HTTP Client Selection\n116: \n117: **Choice**: `requests.Session`\n118: \n119: **Rationale**:\n120: - Mature and widely-used HTTP client\n121: - Built-in connection pooling\n122: - Simple, intuitive API\n123: - Good documentation and community support\n124: \n125: ### Session Management Strategy\n126: \n127: **Choice**: Bootstrap session ID via GET request\n128: \n129: **Rationale**:\n130: - Router manages session lifecycle\n131: - No Control Plane involvement needed\n132: - Simple and stateless\n133: - Supports session reuse\n134: \n135: **Implementation**:\n136: 1. `AgentRuntimeClient` initializes `AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient`\n137: 2. If `session_id` not provided, call `bootstrap_session_id()`\n138: 3. GET on invocation URL returns `x-agentcube-session-id` header\n139: 4. POST requests use the session ID header\n140: \n141: ### Timeout Configuration Strategy\n142: \n143: **Choice**: Configurable defaults with per-call override\n144: \n145: **Rationale**:\n146: - Different workloads have different timeout needs\n147: - Support global defaults\n148: - Allow per-invocation override\n149: \n150: **Configuration**:\n151: 1. Default connect timeout: 5.0 seconds\n152: 2. Default read timeout: 120 seconds\n153: 3. Invoke method accepts optional `timeout` parameter\n154: 4. Timeout tuple: `(connect_timeout, read_timeout)`\n155: \n156: ### Error Handling Strategy\n157: \n158: **Choice**: Standard exceptions with clear messages\n159: \n160: **Rationale**:\n161: - Python's exception hierarchy is sufficient\n162: - `requests` provides detailed HTTP errors\n163: - Custom `ValueError` for missing session ID\n164: - Simpler than custom exception hierarchy\n165: \n166: ### Configuration Resolution Strategy\n167: \n168: **Choice**: Parameter priority over environment variables\n169: \n170: **Rationale**:\n171: - Provide flexibility\n172: - Support different deployment scenarios\n173: - Ease of testing\n174: \n175: **Priority**:\n176: 1. Constructor parameters\n177: 2. Environment variable (`ROUTER_URL`)\n178: 3. Default values\n179: \n180: ## Alternatives Considered\n181: \n182: ### Alternative 1: Async HTTP Client\n183: \n184: **Description**: Use `httpx` or `aiohttp` for async API\n185: \n186: **Pros**:\n187: - Supports async operations\n188: - Better concurrency for I/O-bound tasks\n189: \n190: **Cons**:\n191: - Steeper learning curve\n192: - More complex integration\n193: - Not needed for initial use cases\n194: \n195: **Decision**: Rejected - Sync API sufficient for v1, can extend later\n196: \n197: ### Alternative 2: gRPC Protocol\n198: \n199: **Description**: Use gRPC instead of HTTP REST\n200: \n201: **Pros**:\n202: - Efficient binary protocol\n203: - Strong typing\n204: - Built-in streaming support\n205: \n206: **Cons**:\n207: - Requires server-side gRPC support\n208: - More complex deployment\n209: - Harder to debug\n210: \n211: **Decision**: Rejected - HTTP REST is more universal and easier to integrate\n212: \n213: ### Alternative 3: Single Client Class\n214: \n215: **Description**: Merge Data Plane into main client\n216: \n217: **Pros**:\n218: - Simpler API\n219: - Fewer files\n220: \n221: **Cons**:\n222: - Violates single responsibility principle\n223: - Harder to test\n224: - Less flexible\n225: \n226: **Decision**: Rejected - Separate Data Plane client is cleaner\n227: \n228: ### Alternative 4: Control Plane Session Management\n229: \n230: **Description**: Use Control Plane for session creation\n231: \n232: **Pros**:\n233: - Consistent with CodeInterpreterClient\n234: \n235: **Cons**:\n236: - Unnecessary complexity\n237: - Router already handles sessions\n238: - Extra dependencies\n239: \n240: **Decision**: Rejected - Router-only approach is simpler\n241: \n242: ## Implementation Plan\n243: \n244: ### Phase 1: Data Plane Client (Day 1)\n245: \n246: 1. Implement `AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient` class\n247: 2. Implement `bootstrap_session_id()` method\n248: 3. Implement `invoke()` method\n249: 4. Implement `close()` method\n250: 5. Add unit tests\n251: \n252: ### Phase 2: Agent Runtime Client (Day 1-2)\n253: \n254: 1. Implement `AgentRuntimeClient` class\n255: 2. Implement constructor and configuration resolution\n256: 3. Implement context manager (`__enter__` / `__exit__`)\n257: 4. Implement `invoke()` method\n258: 5. Implement `close()` method\n259: 6. Add unit tests\n260: \n261: ### Phase 3: Integration and Testing (Day 2)\n262: \n263: 1. Update `agentcube/__init__.py` exports\n264: 2. Integration tests with Router\n265: 3. E2E testing\n266: 4. Error scenario testing\n267: \n268: ### Phase 4: Documentation (Day 2-3)\n269: \n270: 1. Write API documentation\n271: 2. Create usage examples\n272: 3. Update README\n273: \n274: ## Testing Strategy\n275: \n276: ### Unit Tests\n277: \n278: 1. **AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient Tests**\n279:    - Session ID bootstrap\n280:    - Invoke request construction\n281:    - Session header management\n282:    - Timeout handling\n283:    - Error propagation\n284: \n285: 2. **AgentRuntimeClient Tests**\n286:    - Configuration resolution\n287:    - Session ID initialization\n288:    - Context manager behavior\n289:    - Invoke delegation\n290:    - Cleanup\n291: \n292: ### Integration Tests\n293: \n294: 1. **Router Integration Tests**\n295:    - Bootstrap session ID from real Router\n296:    - Invoke with real payload\n297:    - Session header validation\n298:    - Timeout scenarios\n299: \n300: 2. **E2E Tests**\n301:    - Complete usage flow\n302:    - Context manager lifecycle\n303:    - Error recovery\n304: \n305: ### Mock Tests\n306: \n307: 1. **HTTP Request Mock**\n308:    - Use `responses` or similar to mock HTTP\n309:    - Test various response scenarios\n310:    - Test error conditions\n311: \n312: ## API Specification\n313: \n314: ### AgentRuntimeClient\n315: \n316: ```python\n317: class AgentRuntimeClient:\n318:     def __init__(\n319:         self,\n320:         agent_name: str,\n321:         namespace: str = \"default\",\n322:         router_url: str | None = None,\n323:         verbose: bool = False,\n324:         session_id: str | None = None,\n325:         timeout: int = 120,\n326:         connect_timeout: float = 5.0,\n327:     ) -> None\n328: \n329:     def __enter__(self) -> \"AgentRuntimeClient\"\n330:     def __exit__(self, exc_type, exc_val, exc_tb) -> None\n331: \n332:     def invoke(self, payload: dict[str, object], timeout: float | None = None) -> dict[str, object]\n333: \n334:     def close(self) -> None\n335: ```\n336: \n337: ### AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient\n338: \n339: ```python\n340: class AgentRuntimeDataPlaneClient:\n341:     SESSION_HEADER = \"x-agentcube-session-id\"\n342: \n343:     def __init__(\n344:         self,\n345:         router_url: str,\n346:         namespace: str,\n347:         agent_name: str,\n348:         timeout: int = 120,\n349:         connect_timeout: float = 5.0,\n350:         pool_connections: int = 10,\n351:         pool_maxsize: int = 10,\n352:     ) -> None\n353: \n354:     def bootstrap_session_id(self) -> str\n355: \n356:     def invoke(self, session_id: str, payload: dict[str, Any], timeout: float | None = None) -> requests.Response\n357: \n358:     def close(self) -> None\n359: ```\n360: \n361: ### HTTP Endpoints\n362: \n363: - `GET {router}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/` - Bootstrap session ID\n364:   - Returns: `x-agentcube-session-id` header\n365: \n366: - `POST {router}/v1/namespaces/{namespace}/agent-runtimes/{agent_name}/invocations/` - Invoke agent\n367:   - Headers: `x-agentcube-session-id`, `Content-Type: application/json`\n368:   - Body: JSON payload\n369: \n370: ## Configuration\n371: \n372: ### Environment Variables\n373: \n374: | Variable | Description | Default |\n375: |----------|-------------|---------|\n376: | `ROUTER_URL` | Router service URL | Required |\n377: \n378: ### Constructor Parameters\n379: \n380: | Parameter | Type | Default | Description |\n381: |-----------|------|---------|-------------|\n382: | `agent_name` | str | Required | Agent runtime name |\n383: | `namespace` | str | \"default\" | Kubernetes namespace |\n384: | `router_url` | str \\| None | None | Router URL |\n385: | `verbose` | bool | False | Enable verbose logging |\n386: | `session_id` | str \\| None | None | Existing session ID to reuse |\n387: | `timeout` | int | 120 | Read timeout in seconds |\n388: | `connect_timeout` | float | 5.0 | Connect timeout in seconds |\n389: \n390: ## Performance Considerations\n391: \n392: 1. **Connection Pooling**\n393:    - `requests.Session` with `HTTPAdapter`\n394:    - Default pool size: 10\n395:    - Reduces connection overhead\n396: \n397: 2. **Timeout Configuration**\n398:    - Reasonable defaults\n399:    - Prevents indefinite hangs\n400:    - Per-call override support\n401: \n402: 3. **Session Reuse**\n403:    - Existing `session_id` can be passed\n404:    - Avoids extra GET request\n405:    - Multiple invocations share session\n406: \n407: ## Security Considerations\n408: \n409: 1. **Session Management**\n410:    - Router handles session validation\n411:    - Session ID transmitted via headers\n412:    - No auth token directly managed\n413: \n414: 2. **Input Validation**\n415:    - Session ID checked before invoke\n416:    - Type hints for API contracts\n417:    - Payloads must be JSON-serializable\n418: \n419: 3. **Logging Security**\n420:    - No sensitive data in logs\n421:    - Session ID may be logged (consider filtering)\n422: \n423: ## Monitoring and Metrics\n424: \n425: ### Key Metrics\n426: \n427: 1. **Client Metrics**\n428:    - Request count\n429:    - Request latency\n430:    - Error rate\n431: \n432: 2. **Session Metrics**\n433:    - Session bootstrap count\n434:    - Session reuse count\n435: \n436: 3. **Invocation Metrics**\n437:    - Invocation count\n438:    - Success rate\n439:    - Invocation latency\n440: \n441: ### Logging\n442: \n443: 1. **Request Logs**\n444:    - HTTP requests/responses\n445:    - Session IDs\n446:    - Timestamps\n447: \n448: 2. **Error Logs**\n449:    - Error types\n450:    - Error messages\n451:    - Stack traces\n452: \n453: 3. **Debug Logs**\n454:    - Configuration details\n455:    - Session bootstrap\n456:    - Request details\n457: \n458: ## Open Questions\n459: \n460: 1. **Q1**: Should we implement retry logic for transient failures?\n461:    - **Current**: No retry logic\n462:    - **Discussion**: Could improve reliability\n463:    - **Decision**: Not in v1, can be added later\n464: \n465: 2. **Q2**: Should we support async API?\n466:    - **Current**: Sync-only\n467:    - **Discussion**: Async may improve performance for concurrent invocations\n468:    - **Decision**: Not in v1, can be added later\n469: \n470: 3. **Q3**: Should we expose metrics?\n471:    - **Current**: No metrics collection\n472:    - **Discussion**: Would help with observability\n473:    - **Decision**: Not in v1, can be added later\n474: \n475: ## Success Criteria\n476: \n477: - Unit tests pass with >80% coverage\n478: - Integration tests pass with real Router\n479: - API documentation complete and accurate\n480: - Example code works end-to-end\n481: - Performance meets requirements (P99 latency < 200ms)\n482: - Zero security vulnerabilities\n483: - Package publishes successfully to PyPI\n484: \n485: ## References\n486: \n487: - [Python SDK Design](../../python-sdk/design.md)\n488: - [Python SDK Spec](../../python-sdk/spec.md)\n489: - [Requests Documentation](https://requests.readthedocs.io/)\n\n(End of file - total 489 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-028: SDK AgentRuntimeClient\n\n## Overview\n\nImplement the `AgentRuntimeClient` in the AgentCube Python SDK, providing a streamlined interface for invoking agent runtime workloads through the Router service. The client abstracts underlying HTTP communication, offering a simple, type-safe API for managing agent runtime sessions and invoking agent workloads with minimal boilerplate.\n\n## Purpose\n\nProvide a Python SDK client for the AgentRuntime service with the following goals:\n\n- Simple, intuitive API for invoking agent runtime workloads\n- Automatic session ID bootstrap and management\n- Context manager support for automatic resource cleanup\n- Integrated Data Plane communication via Router\n- Proper error handling and timeout configuration\n- Detailed logging and debugging support\n\n## Module\n\n`sdk-python`","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-4.7_20260410T163120Z/changes/AR-028/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775878133936,"end":1775878133953}}}}
